ontgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Skipsey, Yorks, England, Greata Britain":"Yorkshire, Engleska, United Kingdom"},"cs":{"1072–":"1072–Zesnulá","1066–Male":"1066–Zesnulý","1098–1136":"1098–1136","1100–Female":"1100–Zesnulá","1072–Female":"1072–Zesnulá","ABT 1098":"okolo 1098","1136":"1136","Abt 1100":"okolo 1100","1100":"1100","1066":"1066","1098":"1098","1072":"1072","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Anglie, United Kingdom","St. Quinton Castle,, Wales":"Castle, Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Skipsey, Yorks, England, Greata Britain":"Yorkshire, Anglie, United Kingdom"},"da":{"1072–":"1072–Afdød","1066–Male":"1066–Afdød","1098–1136":"1098–1136","1100–Female":"1100–Afdød","1072–Female":"1072–Afdød","ABT 1098":"omkring 1098","1136":"1136","Abt 1100":"omkring 1100","1100":"1100","1066":"1066","1098":"1098","1072":"1072","Yorkshire, England":"Jórvík, England, United Kingdom","St. Quinton Castle,, Wales":"Castle, Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Skipsey, Yorks, England, Greata Britain":"Jórvík, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1072–":"1072–Overleden","1066–Male":"1066–Overleden","1098–1136":"1098–1136","1100–Female":"1100–Overleden","1072–Female":"1072–Overleden","ABT 1098":"circa 1098","1136":"1136","Abt 1100":"circa 1100","1100":"1100","1066":"1066","1098":"1098","1072":"1072","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","St. Quinton Castle,, Wales":"Castle, Montgomeryshire, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Skipsey, Yorks, England, Greata Britain":"Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1072–":"1072–Deceased","1066–Male":"1066–Deceased","1098–1136":"1098–1136","1100–Female":"1100–Deceased","1072–Female":"1072–Deceased","ABT 1098":"about 1098","1136":"1136","Abt 1100":"about 1100","1100":"1100","1066":"1066","1098":"1098","1072":"1072","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","St. Quinton Castle,, Wales":"Castle, Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Skipsey, Yorks, England, Greata Britain":"Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Saint","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Cyr, Remy.","English and French: nickname for a particularly pious individual, from Old French and Middle English <i>saint(e)</i>, <i>seint(e)</i> ‘holy’ (from Latin <i>sanctus</i> ‘blameless, holy’). The vocabulary word was occasionally used in the Middle Ages as a personal name and this may have given rise to some instances of the surname.","English: perhaps a nickname for someone who wore, made, or sold girdles, from Middle English <i>ceint</i>, <i>seint</i>, <i>saint</i> ‘girdle’ (Old French <i>ceint</i>, Latin <i>cinctum</i>). Compare   Center  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Center","meanings":["English and Scottish (Aberdeenshire): metonymic occupational name from Middle English, Old French <i>ceinture</i>, <i>seinture</i> ‘girdle’, denoting someone who made or sold girdles, or perhaps a nickname for someone who wore a distinctive girdle.","English: variant of   Senter   1.","Americanized form of German   Zehnder   or of some other similar (like-sounding) surname."]},{"name":"Sant","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Krishan, Anagha, Anjali, Arvind, Deepak, Milind, Nilima, Ravindra, Sanjeev, Sanjiv, Vasudev.","English (Cheshire and Staffordshire): variant of   Saint  .","Italian (northeastern): variant of   Santo  ."]},{"name":"Sante","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Luc, Camille, Lucien.  Spanish Alejandro, Anselmo, Carlos, Emilio, Jesusa, Jorge.","French (also <b>Santé</b>): probably a nickname for a healthy person, from French <i>santé</i> ‘good health’.","Galician, Asturian-Leonese, and Spanish (southwestern): habitational name from one of several places called Sante, in Galicia, Portugal, and Asturias, from a Visigothic personal name. This surname is also found in the Philippines."]}]},{"name":"Quintin","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Yves, Andre, Dominique, Gilles, Lucien, Michel, Oliva, Roch.","Breton: from the personal name <i>Quintin</i>, which is of the same Latin origin as 2 below, but also considered a derivative of Old Breton <i>kint</i> ‘first’.","French; Spanish (<b>Quintín</b>): from the personal name <i>Quintin</i> (Spanish <i>Quintín</i>), from Latin <i>Quintinus</i>, a Christian saint's name (see   Quentin  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Quinton","meanings":["English: from the Old French and Middle English personal name <i>Quentin</i>, <i>Quintin</i> (Latin <i>Quintinus</i>, a suffixed form of <i>quintus</i> ‘fifth’), popular in France from the cult of Saint Quentin of Amiens, and brought to England by the Normans. The surname was altered to <i>Quinton</i> by association with the placenames in 2 below.","English: habitational name from from any of three places called Quinton (Gloucestershire, Northamptonshire, Worcestershire) or from Quainton (Buckinghamshire). The placenames probably derive from Old English <i>cwēn</i> ‘queen’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’, or perhaps from Old English <i>cwene</i> ‘woman’ + <i>tūn</i> or an Old English personal name <i>Cwēna</i> + Old English connective <i>-ing-</i> + <i>tūn</i>.","English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Saint-Quentin (Manche) in France or possibly from Saint-Quentin-en-Tourmont (Somme), the site of the martyrdom of Saint Quentin of Amiens, a 3rd-century Roman missionary to Gaul. It is not certain that this surname survived into the modern period."]},{"name":"Quentin","meanings":["French: from the Old French personal name <i>Quentin</i> (from Latin <i>Quintinus</i>, a suffixed form of <i>quintus</i> ‘fifth’), popular in France from the cult of Saint Quentin of Amiens, a 3rd-century Roman missionary to Gaul. Compare   Quintin  .","English: variant of   Quinton  ."]}]},{"name":"Herbert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, introduced to Britain by the Normans. It is derived from <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. An Old English form, <i>Herebeorht</i>, existed in England before the Conquest, but was superseded by the Norman form, which gave rise to an important surname. The family in question were earls of Pembroke in the 16th and 17th centuries; they included the poet  George Herbert . By the end of the Middle Ages <i>Herbert</i> was little used, although it remained a favourite with some families, notably the Saint Quintins of East Yorkshire. Its greater frequency in Britain from the 19th century onwards is due partly to the trend for the revival of medieval names of Germanic origin and partly to the trend for the transferred use of surnames."],"variants":[{"name":"Heribert","meanings":["From an Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, introduced to Britain by the Normans. It is derived from <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. An Old English form, <i>Herebeorht</i>, existed in England before the Conquest, but was superseded by the Norman form, which gave rise to an important surname. The family in question were earls of Pembroke in the 16th and 17th centuries; they included the poet  George Herbert . By the end of the Middle Ages <i>Herbert</i> was little used, although it remained a favourite with some families, notably the Saint Quintins of East Yorkshire. Its greater frequency in Britain from the 19th century onwards is due partly to the trend for the revival of medieval names of Germanic origin and partly to the trend for the transferred use of surnames."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Herbert Saint Quintin was born in 1072, in Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Sir Herbert Quintin I."},"et":{"1072–":"1072–S